current design to apply Arial Unicode MS font against Japanese text displayed on Translation Results / Edit Translation Units windows may need to be revised for the following reason.\r\n\r\nThis font is not the most suitable type for displaying Japanese text at least (we need ask for input about Chinese and Korean text from the native language users). \r\n\r\nIt is true that this font is recommended for Unicode characters in Windows as a safe option to prevent the character corruption. \r\nHowever, when applied as is, the characters appear rather unprofessional as the shape, layout and strokes of the most characters appear very awkward and misaligned.\r\nThere seems to be several discussion threads / blogs by Japanese Windows users commenting on this font (not specific to Studio application).\r\n\r\nCurrently, there are 2 viable solutions proposed:\r\n*1)* adapt the font fall back implemented on Fragment Matches window (currently, MS Gothic UI is specified for Japanese)\r\n*2)* use the method of ClearType antialiasing against this old font (Atial Unicode MS) may improve this out-of-date look:\r\nhttps://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/dd183433(v=vs.85).aspx\r\n\r\nNOTE: While the solution *1)* may be more favoured, [~aerdei] has pointed out that it may require extensive modifications against the legacy code, which involves changing the whole logic of the Editor.\r\nOnce the decision is finalise against this, we can seek the advice on the most ideal font for
